title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message:
First off, completely dead board (another thread).
Got the board starting but fan spins constantly with no light on USB mouse.
No CPU VCORE and PP1V05_S0 at 0.2V.
Found a short on U7400 and replaced it. Now i have PP1V05_S0 But still no CPU VCORE

Found that All_Sys_PWRGD was missing so I replaced U1950 and I have now got 3,8V there.

Still no CPU VCORE, Pin 20 and 22 on U7200 gives me nothing.

Should I just replace U7200 or look elsewhere?

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message:
An update, the missing CPU VCORE seems to be my fault, poor U6100 soldering, have now got 1V on pin 20 and 22 on U7200 and I have got CPU VCORE.
Fan still spins constantly and no light on USB mouse.

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: Hmm, CPU VCORE Missing again so probably something else :(

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message:
My god, now all_sys_pwrgd is missing again. It seems like I jumped to a conclusion a little to fast. It seems like CPU VCORE and ALL_SYS_PWRGD comes and goes.
Anyone got any ideas?

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: ALL_SYS_PWRGD is going to come from PP1V5_S0 PP3V3_S0 PP5V_S0 working. If they are all present then look carefully for corrosion in the Q8150 area. This board and the measurements you're giving sound like a ping pong ball you're holding down in water with one finger though so I don't have high hopes here.

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: So it is power cycling. The usual shit: U6100 and termination resistors/traces, U1950 pin 8...

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: No it is not power cycling, when I do get CPU VCORE and ALL_SYS_PWRGD they stay high but I get no boot, only fan spin. I have replaced U1950 and tried with another U6100. All resistors look good but maybe a bad capacitor or something. I'll check Q8150.

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: Q8150 looked fine but I replaced it anyway, unfortunately it's the same :(

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: Put back original U6100. Besides that it will probably corrosion under the SMC or some other rabbit hole...

title: 820-3437 Rabbit hole
message: I have already put back the original U6100 since it didn't make any difference, I guess I'll try an SMC reflow first and then replace or re-ball.
